I'm sorry, love.

465
00:40:12,743 --> 00:40:15,371
Get rid of this for me.

466
00:40:22,553 --> 00:40:24,544
<i>[ Chattering]</i>

467
00:40:26,424 --> 00:40:28,756
Watch your step.

468
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:38,834
Prisoner transfer.
Yes, sir?

469
00:40:38,903 --> 00:40:41,929
Intelligence wants a word with this guy.
Let him through.

470
00:40:49,914 --> 00:40:51,905
All right. Looking good.

471
00:40:59,123 --> 00:41:02,217
<i>[Mike]
Okay. This is great.
Just what I need.</i>

472
00:41:03,661 --> 00:41:05,652
[Sighs]

473
00:41:08,299 --> 00:41:11,700
<i>Keep your mouth shut, Fazal.
Understand?</i>

474
00:41:12,970 --> 00:41:14,801
[Chattering]

475
00:41:14,872 --> 00:41:18,808
Come on. Come on.
Move out of the friggin' way, man.

476
00:41:20,911 --> 00:41:22,902
Just be nice to me.

477
00:41:25,616 --> 00:41:27,243
<i>Hold it.</i>

478
00:41:27,318 --> 00:41:29,582
You're good. Go ahead.
Thanks.

479
00:41:30,588 --> 00:41:32,647
<i>[Man Speaking Foreign Language]</i>

480
00:41:42,800 --> 00:41:44,495
<i>[ Doorbell Buzzes]</i>

481
00:41:50,641 --> 00:41:52,768
Yes?

482
00:41:52,843 --> 00:41:55,243
Zula.
I'll be right there.

483
00:41:56,347 --> 00:41:58,508
<i>[ Cell Phone Ringing]</i>

484
00:42:00,451 --> 00:42:02,612
<i>- Hello.
- [Man]
Alex,</i>

485
00:42:02,686 --> 00:42:04,677
<i>your container from
Greater Orient's been hijacked.</i>

486
00:42:04,755 --> 00:42:06,689
<i>It's been what?</i>

487
00:42:06,757 --> 00:42:08,384
<i>The whole shipment's
been cleaned out.</i>

488
00:42:08,459 --> 00:42:10,586
Everything?

489
00:42:10,661 --> 00:42:12,959
<i>Sorry, Alex.
Everything.</i>

490
00:42:14,798 --> 00:42:17,232
I'll get back to you.

491
00:42:23,173 --> 00:42:25,164
[Whimpers]

492
00:42:31,982 --> 00:42:34,382
What?
Have you heard anything...

493
00:42:34,451 --> 00:42:36,976
about your sister?

494
00:42:37,054 --> 00:42:39,022
No.

495
00:42:39,089 --> 00:42:42,286
The ship they were supposed to
be coming in on, it, uh...

496
00:42:43,294 --> 00:42:45,262
I heard it's...
What?

497
00:42:45,329 --> 00:42:48,389
I heard that it's gone down.

498
00:42:48,465 --> 00:42:51,559
No. No, no.

499
00:42:58,342 --> 00:43:00,776
<i>[ Cell Phone Rings]</i>

500
00:43:00,844 --> 00:43:02,835
<i>[Elevator Bell Dings]</i>

501
00:43:02,913 --> 00:43:04,904
<i>Excuse me.
[Ringing Continues]</i>

502
00:43:06,317 --> 00:43:08,410
Excuse me.

503
00:43:11,121 --> 00:43:13,112
Hello.
[Alex]
It's me.

504
00:43:14,425 --> 00:43:17,826
The shipment for
the Shirt Palace was hijacked.

505
00:43:17,895 --> 00:43:21,661
What? Where?
They took
every single piece inside it.

506
00:43:23,400 --> 00:43:25,868
- None of it was insured.
- Dad,

507
00:43:25,936 --> 00:43:27,870
what... what kind of business
are you running?

508
00:43:27,938 --> 00:43:30,498
I've been running this place
single-handed since your mom died.

509
00:43:30,574 --> 00:43:32,804
Do you think it's easy
to make a living in this business?

510
00:43:32,876 --> 00:43:36,869
Dad...
You know how many companies
go to the wall every year?

511
00:43:36,947 --> 00:43:41,043
You didn't exactly turn out to be
the... the Bill Gates
of the real estate world, did ya?

512
00:43:44,188 --> 00:43:47,453
Huh? Dad.

513
00:43:53,631 --> 00:43:55,861
<i>Dad? Dad?</i>

514
00:44:16,854 --> 00:44:19,254
- Hey, uh...
- Where is this place?

515
00:44:19,323 --> 00:44:22,656
If I told you that,
you wouldn't need me,
now, would ya?

516
00:44:22,726 --> 00:44:24,717
Cousin.

517
00:44:27,831 --> 00:44:31,028
You have to earn the right
to call someone ''cousin.''

518
00:44:33,837 --> 00:44:36,101
<i>[Adam]
I don't know if it is that ship.</i>

519
00:44:36,173 --> 00:44:38,573
<i>I keep telling myself it can't be.</i>

520
00:44:38,642 --> 00:44:40,610
But if it is... if it's true...

521
00:44:40,678 --> 00:44:42,612
nobody made it off ship.

522
00:44:42,680 --> 00:44:44,705
<i>Nobody.
Not one person survive.</i>

523
00:44:52,122 --> 00:44:54,147
You...

524
00:44:54,224 --> 00:44:56,522
You put my sister on that ship.

525
00:45:02,966 --> 00:45:07,130
I don't even know what happened.
You put her on it
with her little girl.

526
00:45:08,372 --> 00:45:11,535
I... I came in the same way.
The same people.

527
00:45:11,608 --> 00:45:13,906
So did you.
You know how dangerous it is.

528
00:45:16,346 --> 00:45:18,337
You know.

529
00:45:19,783 --> 00:45:21,774
Yes.

530
00:45:21,852 --> 00:45:23,843
Hey, I am sorry.

531
00:45:24,955 --> 00:45:27,219
[Exhales deeply]

532
00:45:27,291 --> 00:45:31,227
I just want... them here.

533
00:45:31,295 --> 00:45:34,059
That's all.
I just want us together again.

534
00:45:34,131 --> 00:45:36,292
<i>[ Door Opens]
[Woman]
Zula.</i>

535
00:45:37,468 --> 00:45:40,767
Sarah has a make-up ballet class
after her art lesson.

536
00:45:40,838 --> 00:45:43,466
<i>- Can you pick her up
before Polly's piano lesson?
- Yes.</i>

537
00:45:46,410 --> 00:45:49,174
<i>Are you here about
the water filter?</i>

538
00:45:49,246 --> 00:45:52,306
Uh, no, no.
He is my brother-in-law.

539
00:45:52,382 --> 00:45:54,816
Oh, sorry. Hi.

540
00:45:55,819 --> 00:45:58,879
<i>I'll leave you two alone.
Nice to have met you.</i>

541
00:46:05,395 --> 00:46:08,262
Hey.
Hey.

542
00:46:08,332 --> 00:46:11,028
- [Woman]
Okay. Bye-bye, Ronny.
- How is he?

543
00:46:12,703 --> 00:46:16,002
<i>[Machine Beeping]
[Ben]
We'll know in a few hours.</i>

544
00:46:16,073 --> 00:46:18,007
I hear he, uh, lost the container.

545
00:46:18,075 --> 00:46:20,543
Something travels
halfway around the world,

546
00:46:20,611 --> 00:46:23,102
gets to Seattle and... Phoom...
just like that.

547
00:46:23,180 --> 00:46:25,205
There's a lot of bad people
out there.

548
00:46:25,282 --> 00:46:28,649
Yeah. But this shipment
was pretty special.

549
00:46:28,719 --> 00:46:30,653
Your dad really needed this one.

550
00:46:30,721 --> 00:46:33,781
I mean, he really needed this one.

551
00:46:33,857 --> 00:46:35,791
<i>Your dad had
a cash flow problem.</i>

552
00:46:35,859 --> 00:46:39,056
I put him in touch with somebody,
the loan was secured on that shipment...

553
00:46:39,129 --> 00:46:41,063
for 250,000.

554
00:46:41,131 --> 00:46:43,065
Uh,

555
00:46:43,133 --> 00:46:45,124
do you have documentation?

556
00:46:46,303 --> 00:46:50,205
Yeah, well, your father
and the lender wanted to
keep it off the books.

557
00:46:50,274 --> 00:46:52,401
I mean, did somebody say ''I.R.S.''?

558
00:46:52,476 --> 00:46:56,344
- I need to speak to the lender.
- Ehh! Wrong.
That isn't how it works.

559
00:46:56,413 --> 00:47:01,009
<i>My dad told me about guanxi...
I do a favor for you,
you do one for me.</i>

560
00:47:01,084 --> 00:47:03,678
<i>- And I can't run a business that way.
- Guanxi?</i>

561
00:47:03,754 --> 00:47:07,246
What is that?
Some kind of old Chinese shtick?
Talk American to me, okay?

562
00:47:07,324 --> 00:47:11,658
Look. I need paperwork, documents,
some kind of verification of funds.
Ehh!

563
00:47:11,728 --> 00:47:15,494
Wrong again.
You have to start listening.
This is how it's done.

564
00:47:15,566 --> 00:47:18,729
No, this is how it's done.
I'm taking over
until my dad gets better.

565
00:47:18,802 --> 00:47:21,134
I didn't ask for it, but I'm doing it.

566
00:47:21,205 --> 00:47:23,503
Yeah, like you did
that property development, right?

567
00:47:24,741 --> 00:47:27,335
Yeah, developing lofts downtown.

568
00:47:27,411 --> 00:47:30,869
What was it the banks foreclosed
on you for that? Five million?

569
00:47:30,948 --> 00:47:34,907
Guess you're not looking for
Young Businessman of the Year, huh?

570
00:47:43,627 --> 00:47:45,561
Hey.
No.

571
00:47:45,629 --> 00:47:47,722
No, no, no.
It's not that.
It's not that.

572
00:47:47,798 --> 00:47:49,629
He's okay?
He's fine.

573
00:47:49,700 --> 00:47:51,759
What are you doing here?
I'm working here.
How you doin'?

574
00:47:51,835 --> 00:47:54,633
Oh, my God.
God, you're a sight for sore eyes.

575
00:47:54,705 --> 00:47:57,640
Come in, come in, come in.
He's okay?
Yeah, yeah. No, he's fine.

576
00:47:57,708 --> 00:47:59,642
When did you get here?
I just got here.

577
00:47:59,710 --> 00:48:03,669
<i>Uh, 14 hours in the hold of a C-14
and no in-flight movie and, you know...</i>

578
00:48:03,747 --> 00:48:06,341
Oh, my God.
It's so good to see you. God.

579
00:48:06,416 --> 00:48:08,350
This is a nice place.
Yeah, yeah.

580
00:48:08,418 --> 00:48:11,444
We have so much to do. Come in.
Let me get you something to drink.

581
00:48:30,641 --> 00:48:33,109
Lieutenant, we found
Mike's vehicle.

582
00:48:36,146 --> 00:48:38,637
<i>[Man]
Yeah, it's Mike McKay's jeep.</i>

583
00:48:38,715 --> 00:48:40,649
It doesn't look good.

584
00:48:40,717 --> 00:48:42,810
It's been riddled with small arms fire.

585
00:48:43,887 --> 00:48:47,152
<i>AK- 47. No bodies.</i>

586
00:48:47,224 --> 00:48:49,488
Everything suggests
he's been taken through a minefield.

587
00:48:53,163 --> 00:48:56,257
Really.
He misses you and Tyler.

588
00:48:56,333 --> 00:48:59,200
I'm so sorry about before.
I really am.

589
00:48:59,269 --> 00:49:02,363
It's just that Mike always said
that if anything ever happened to him,

590
00:49:02,439 --> 00:49:04,839
you know, it would be you
who came to tell us.

591
00:49:04,908 --> 00:49:07,672
It's not like that.
He just wanted me to
check in on you guys,

592
00:49:07,744 --> 00:49:09,678
see how the move was going.
Yeah, well,

593
00:49:09,746 --> 00:49:12,681
<i>the move could be going
a little more quickly.</i>

594
00:49:12,749 --> 00:49:15,513
This is gonna be an office... someday.
Well, it's getting there.

595
00:49:15,585 --> 00:49:18,076
Look. Do you need help
with, uh, these boxes?

596
00:49:18,155 --> 00:49:20,089
Uh, yeah.

597
00:49:20,157 --> 00:49:21,681
Where's this go?
These are all up.

598
00:49:21,758 --> 00:49:23,817
So when'd you speak to him last?

599
00:49:23,894 --> 00:49:26,089
<i>Uh, Thanksgiving.
[ Chuckles]</i>

600
00:49:26,163 --> 00:49:28,188
<i>Where am I going?
Straight ahead.</i>

601
00:49:28,265 --> 00:49:31,598
Where are they going?
Oh, God knows.

602
00:49:31,668 --> 00:49:35,627
Could be across the border
in Pakistan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan,

603
00:49:35,706 --> 00:49:39,039
or any other couple of
million square miles
of pissant nothing.

604
00:49:39,109 --> 00:49:42,875
How do we know he's still alive?
Maybe you should be
hoping he's not.

605
00:49:42,946 --> 00:49:46,074
<i>Remember that C.I.A. Station chief
the Lebanese tortured on camera?</i>

606
00:49:46,149 --> 00:49:49,550
How did he sound?
Uh, I don't know.

607
00:49:49,619 --> 00:49:51,553
A little odd, actually.

608
00:49:51,621 --> 00:49:54,556
He said something like,
uh, even if it gets tough,

609
00:49:55,559 --> 00:49:58,926
for me not to worry...
that it's all about Tyler and me.

610
00:49:58,996 --> 00:50:00,930
''Even if it gets tough,'' huh?
Yeah.

611
00:50:00,998 --> 00:50:03,865
Wonder what he meant by that.
I don't know.
I got cut off.

612
00:50:03,934 --> 00:50:06,266
I didn't get a chance to ask him.

613
00:50:06,336 --> 00:50:09,635
It's odd really. You know,
he usually keeps everything inside.

614
00:50:09,706 --> 00:50:11,640
[Mike]
This guy.
[Fazal] Yes?

615
00:50:11,708 --> 00:50:14,336
Yeah.

616
00:50:14,411 --> 00:50:16,402
And that guy right there.

617
00:50:16,480 --> 00:50:18,471
Oh.

618
00:50:26,223 --> 00:50:27,986
<i>This guy here.
Yes.</i>

619
00:50:28,058 --> 00:50:29,992
- The guy there... definitely.
- [Foreign Language]

620
00:50:30,060 --> 00:50:32,255
<i>[Horse Whinnies]</i>

621
00:50:34,498 --> 00:50:35,863
<i>This guy.</i>

622
00:50:35,932 --> 00:50:38,093
Yes.

623
00:50:41,004 --> 00:50:43,598
[Foreign Language]
Ah.

624
00:50:43,673 --> 00:50:45,664
Definitely him.

625
00:50:50,113 --> 00:50:52,377
- This guy right here.
- Oh. Sure.

626
00:50:53,617 --> 00:50:55,551
Good.

627
00:51:01,925 --> 00:51:04,450
<i>[Tyler]
Hold on. Hold on.</i>

628
00:51:04,528 --> 00:51:07,122
Oh, hey, big man.
How you doin'?

629
00:51:07,197 --> 00:51:09,131
You gonna help your mom
with these boxes?

630
00:51:09,199 --> 00:51:11,360
<i>- I don't know.
Are you my dad?
- No, I'm not.</i>

631
00:51:11,435 --> 00:51:14,871
I'm your dad's best buddy.
If he's not here to whip your ass,
he said I should do it.

632
00:51:14,938 --> 00:51:17,304
Put your weight on the back foot.
Back foot.

633
00:51:17,374 --> 00:51:20,810
Come on. Come on.
Come on. Come on, you...

634
00:51:21,945 --> 00:51:25,642
If you don't pull your weight
around here with Mama,
you better answer to me, chief.

635
00:51:25,715 --> 00:51:27,307
Dig it?

636
00:51:27,384 --> 00:51:30,876
You ready?
We leave right now?

637
00:51:30,954 --> 00:51:34,720
Travel fast and light,
under everybody's radar screen.

638
00:51:34,791 --> 00:51:36,759
We get in, we get out.

639
00:51:36,827 --> 00:51:39,990
- Granny is still sitting on the porch.
- Sippin' her lemonade.

640
00:51:40,063 --> 00:51:42,497
[Speaks Foreign Language]

641
00:51:42,566 --> 00:51:45,330
<i>Wait, please.
Let me see your map.</i>

642
00:51:45,402 --> 00:51:48,394
Map, map, map. Oh.

643
00:51:48,472 --> 00:51:50,497
<i>It's all up here.
[Horse Whinnying]</i>

644
00:51:53,310 --> 00:51:55,642
<i>[Mike]
Yeeeee-ha.!</i>

645
00:51:55,712 --> 00:51:57,942
<i>- All right?
- Yeah, I won't make you work.</i>

646
00:51:58,014 --> 00:52:01,950
- I promise.
You can just come over and eat.
- If Mike gets in touch again, let me know.

647
00:52:02,018 --> 00:52:03,679
I will.
He owes me a couple of beers.

648
00:52:03,753 --> 00:52:05,448
<i>Later.
See ya.
Be good to your mother.</i>

649
00:52:05,522 --> 00:52:07,456
Maybe.

650
00:52:07,524 --> 00:52:09,492
Bye. Thank you so much.
All right.

651
00:52:11,328 --> 00:52:13,296
<i>See ya.
Bye.</i>

652
00:52:14,364 --> 00:52:16,855
<i>Did he say exactly
when Dad was coming back?</i>

653
00:52:16,933 --> 00:52:19,527
No. Just that he'd be a little longer
than he thought he'd be.

654
00:52:19,603 --> 00:52:21,537
Like Christmas?
I hope so.

655
00:52:21,605 --> 00:52:24,597
Maybe Christmas next year?
Oh, maybe.
When'd you get to be so funny?

656
00:52:24,674 --> 00:52:27,370
You're really...
You're really comin' along
with the comedy.

657
00:52:30,947 --> 00:52:32,938
[Engine Starts]

658
00:52:38,188 --> 00:52:40,622
I gotta know
what we're into these guys for.

659
00:52:43,260 --> 00:52:45,820
I mean, you know,
what are we looking at?

660
00:52:49,065 --> 00:52:51,226
[Breathing Erratically]

661
00:52:55,805 --> 00:52:57,739
[No Audible dialogue]

662
00:53:08,251 --> 00:53:10,242
I love you, dad.

663
00:53:17,661 --> 00:53:20,425
<i>[ Doorbell Rings]</i>

664
00:53:26,770 --> 00:53:28,931
Afternoon. Alarm company.

665
00:53:30,340 --> 00:53:32,331
Thanks.

666
00:53:33,777 --> 00:53:35,904
Any idea where the control panel is?

667
00:53:37,581 --> 00:53:39,515
Oh, no.
I have no idea.

668
00:53:39,583 --> 00:53:42,950
It's usually in the laundry room.
Why don't we start there?
Laundry room's there.

669
00:53:43,019 --> 00:53:45,453
- There? Okay, thanks.
- I'm gonna check the window.

670
00:53:45,522 --> 00:53:47,456
<i>Sure.</i>

671
00:53:59,336 --> 00:54:01,327
<i>[ Car Alarm Chirps]</i>

672
00:54:13,216 --> 00:54:15,548
She's at her car.

673
00:54:20,156 --> 00:54:22,090
<i>[Man]
Give me your hand.</i>

674
00:54:26,563 --> 00:54:28,929
As long as they're touching,
you've got a circuit.

675
00:54:28,999 --> 00:54:31,524
- I need to check something upstairs.
- All right.

676
00:54:31,601 --> 00:54:35,162
<i>- You pull them apart,
break the connection and...
- [Alarm Beeping]</i>

677
00:54:35,238 --> 00:54:36,500
All right?

678
00:54:56,259 --> 00:54:58,693
- We're movin'.
- E.T.A.?

679
00:54:58,762 --> 00:55:00,696
<i>Eight to 1 0 minutes.</i>

680
00:55:06,036 --> 00:55:09,597
Frank, we ought to wrap it up.

681
00:55:12,142 --> 00:55:14,133
<i>[Frank]
You're hardwired for smoke and fire.</i>

682
00:55:14,210 --> 00:55:17,941
I've gotta check the fire station
to get an automatic signal.

683
00:55:18,014 --> 00:55:20,642
You mind getting that? Thanks.

684
00:55:28,558 --> 00:55:31,049
Thanks, buddy.

685
00:55:38,702 --> 00:55:41,000
<i>[Man]
She's heading for home.
How you guys doin'?</i>

686
00:55:42,539 --> 00:55:45,303
- We're through in here, aren't we, Frank?
- We're all done.

687
00:55:48,978 --> 00:55:51,037
<i>[Phone Rings]
[ Chattering]</i>

688
00:55:52,649 --> 00:55:55,083
<i>[Man]
I don't want to have to
lie to her again.</i>

689
00:55:55,151 --> 00:55:59,485
<i>I don't want to have to face her son
knowing we don't have any idea
where his father is.</i>

690
00:55:59,556 --> 00:56:02,081
Until we get some answers,
there's no point in telling her any more.

691
00:56:02,158 --> 00:56:04,991
How about the fact
that she's married to him?
He phoned her.

692
00:56:05,061 --> 00:56:08,360
He didn't tell her what he was doing,
where he was going,
when he would contact her?

693
00:56:08,431 --> 00:56:11,662
- That's right.
- Are you sure of that?

694
00:56:11,735 --> 00:56:14,431
Is there something
you want to tell me?
Something I'm missing here?

695
00:56:15,839 --> 00:56:18,603
Your buddy disappeared
in the company of a drug dealer.

696
00:56:18,675 --> 00:56:20,609
Just let me have this one.
Just one. This guy.

697
00:56:20,677 --> 00:56:23,441
<i>[Woman]
A drug dealer he took a lot of risk
to get a hold of.</i>

698
00:56:23,513 --> 00:56:25,447
You want him, you go through me.

699
00:56:25,515 --> 00:56:29,383
You want his wife and his son to know that?
Until we clear up just what happened.

700
00:56:29,452 --> 00:56:31,943
He was ambushed.
They shot up his jeep and grabbed him.

701
00:56:34,224 --> 00:56:36,283
That's what it looks like.
That's how it was.

702
00:56:36,359 --> 00:56:38,589
That's right.

703
00:56:38,661 --> 00:56:40,891
What else could it be?

704
00:56:51,040 --> 00:56:52,473
[Gasps]

705
00:56:52,542 --> 00:56:54,134
<i>[Sighs]</i>

706
00:56:54,210 --> 00:56:55,700
Oh, geez.

707
00:57:00,984 --> 00:57:03,316
Sorry. I'm sorry.

708
00:57:05,622 --> 00:57:09,114
<i>[Ben]
I'm trying to restructure the debt.
I- I just need a couple weeks.</i>

709
00:57:09,192 --> 00:57:11,752
<i>Okay, fine.
Sue our asses off.</i>

710
00:57:11,828 --> 00:57:15,821
We'll go Chapter 11.
You'll be lucky to get
three cents on the dollar.

711
00:57:15,899 --> 00:57:17,833
<i>[Phone Rings]</i>

712
00:57:17,901 --> 00:57:19,994
Hello. He's not in.
I'm running the company until...

713
00:57:20,069 --> 00:57:22,003
<i>[Man]
Ben.! Ben.! Look.! Your car.!</i>

714
00:57:22,071 --> 00:57:25,404
Look! It's on fire!

715
00:57:27,877 --> 00:57:30,345
<i>[Sirens Wailing]</i>

716
00:57:30,413 --> 00:57:32,438
<i>[ Cell Phone Rings]</i>

717
00:57:36,820 --> 00:57:39,584
[Man]
Next time it'll be your house.

718
00:57:42,025 --> 00:57:44,459
<i>[Sirens Wailing]</i>

719
00:57:47,630 --> 00:57:49,621
[Tires Screech]

720
00:57:52,101 --> 00:57:54,228
<i>[Man]
You see anything?</i>

721
00:57:54,304 --> 00:57:56,431
Hear anything?
Somebody running away maybe?

722
00:57:58,141 --> 00:58:00,075
Uh, no. No.

723
00:58:00,143 --> 00:58:04,546
You have any trouble with your neighbors?
Business dispute with anybody?

724
00:58:05,682 --> 00:58:08,344
No, no. Noth...
Nothing like that.

725
00:58:08,418 --> 00:58:11,046
You're fully insured?

726
00:58:12,255 --> 00:58:14,849
Yeah, well,
I-I gotta look into that.

727
00:58:14,924 --> 00:58:17,154
<i>[ Cell Phone Rings]
Excuse me.
I gotta take this.</i>

728
00:58:17,227 --> 00:58:19,195
Yeah?

729
00:58:20,530 --> 00:58:22,498
Yes.

730
00:58:43,820 --> 00:58:47,085
<i>[Knocking On Door]
What?</i>

731
00:58:47,156 --> 00:58:51,092
Did anybody call?
No. Two guys came by
to wire the alarm system.

732
00:58:51,160 --> 00:58:54,254
They said they couldn't come
till next week.

733
00:58:56,232 --> 00:58:58,496
<i>- [Phone Rings]
- That's odd.</i>

734
00:59:00,003 --> 00:59:02,198
Hello. Oh, hi, Mom.

735
00:59:02,272 --> 00:59:04,604
Yeah, no, the move went fine.

736
00:59:04,674 --> 00:59:07,108
Oh, we've had a lot of practice.

737
00:59:07,176 --> 00:59:09,667
<i>[Men Chattering In Foreign Language]</i>

738
00:59:21,958 --> 00:59:23,949
[Foreign Language]

739
00:59:36,873 --> 00:59:39,933
<i>[Fazal]
Gholab? Gholab.</i>

740
00:59:50,954 --> 00:59:53,650
[Screaming]

741
00:59:53,723 --> 00:59:55,748
<i>[Horn Honks]</i>

742
00:59:59,295 --> 01:00:02,162
Wearing your seat belt?
No.

743
01:00:02,231 --> 01:00:05,894
- Come on. Put it on.
How many times I have to tell you?
- Okay. Okay.

744
01:00:10,740 --> 01:00:13,334
<i>[Men Speaking Foreign Language]</i>

745
01:00:14,744 --> 01:00:16,177
[Foreign Language]

746
01:00:16,245 --> 01:00:18,509
This is Gholab.
Hi.

747
01:00:18,581 --> 01:00:20,606
This is an American.
Oh. Hello.

748
01:00:20,683 --> 01:00:22,116
Want to buy.
Hi, mister.

749
01:00:22,185 --> 01:00:25,086
How are you?
[Foreign Language]

750
01:00:25,154 --> 01:00:26,416
[Fazal]
Yes?

751
01:00:26,489 --> 01:00:29,287
- Tell him I'm looking for modern Soviet.
- [Foreign Language]

752
01:00:29,359 --> 01:00:33,352
This is World War II Enfield.
It's from the Second World War.
Tell him to get serious.

753
01:00:33,429 --> 01:00:36,023
[Foreign Language]

754
01:00:36,099 --> 01:00:40,433
- Modern.
- The M16 gave us more headaches
in Vietnam than the Vietcong did.

755
01:00:40,503 --> 01:00:43,028
A bren gun, a tommy gun.
[Scoffs]

756
01:00:44,273 --> 01:00:47,640
- You tell this guy to be serious.
- Yeah. He's got stuff. He's got good stuff.

757
01:00:47,710 --> 01:00:49,143
No, no. Follow.

758
01:00:49,212 --> 01:00:50,611
I'm coming.

759
01:00:53,616 --> 01:00:56,107
- Ah, yes. You see?
- [Foreign Language]

760
01:00:56,185 --> 01:00:58,710
Now you're talking.
[Foreign Language]

761
01:00:58,788 --> 01:01:01,382
Yeah, this is what I'm interested in.

762
01:01:01,457 --> 01:01:03,982
This is what it's...
This is good.
[Foreign Language]

763
01:01:09,399 --> 01:01:11,731
<i>[Man Yelling In Foreign Language]</i>

764
01:01:14,370 --> 01:01:16,463
[Chattering]

765
01:01:21,244 --> 01:01:24,008
<i>[Man]
Hey, good to see ya.
The team's gonna win today?</i>

766
01:01:24,080 --> 01:01:26,480
<i>[Woman]
Go, Ben.</i>

767
01:01:26,549 --> 01:01:30,315
<i>[Woman #2]
All the way.! All the way.!
Come on. Oh.</i>

768
01:01:34,924 --> 01:01:36,892
<i>[ Crowd Yelling, Chattering]</i>

769
01:01:37,894 --> 01:01:41,352
All I want to know is
were they aboard that ship?

770
01:01:42,899 --> 01:01:44,924
I can't tell you
because I don't know.

771
01:01:45,001 --> 01:01:46,935
Nobody knows.

772
01:01:47,003 --> 01:01:49,938
But there are people you could ask...
people who do know.

773
01:01:50,006 --> 01:01:54,033
Look. You've got people
moving all over the world.

774
01:01:54,110 --> 01:01:56,101
Millions of them.

775
01:01:56,179 --> 01:02:00,309
Chinese, Haitians,
Albanians, Kurds... whatever.

776
01:02:00,383 --> 01:02:02,442
Most of them want to come here.

777
01:02:02,518 --> 01:02:05,510
<i>That's what you paid me for...
to bring your family here.</i>

778
01:02:07,523 --> 01:02:09,753
All I know is the ship went down.

779
01:02:11,194 --> 01:02:15,130
If you're serious about
becoming legal... American...

780
01:02:15,198 --> 01:02:18,065
I suggest you drop this.

781
01:02:20,036 --> 01:02:23,233
He's good, huh?
Your son.

782
01:02:25,041 --> 01:02:30,479
Russian guy... soldier...
he... he was found on street of village
where I used to live in Chechnya.

783
01:02:30,546 --> 01:02:33,538
[Chuckles]
He... He fall off truck, drunk.

784
01:02:33,616 --> 01:02:35,641
Break his neck... accident.

785
01:02:35,718 --> 01:02:37,879
But they assumed it was
Chechen guerrillas.

786
01:02:37,954 --> 01:02:42,755
Uh, they demand that the head man
pay for this crime.

787
01:02:42,825 --> 01:02:45,123
He said, ''No.''

788
01:02:46,729 --> 01:02:49,061
They didn't come after him.

789
01:02:49,132 --> 01:02:51,123
Not directly. They, uh...

790
01:02:52,668 --> 01:02:55,330
They kill his daughter,

791
01:02:55,404 --> 01:02:57,895
his son,

792
01:02:57,974 --> 01:02:59,965
his mother...

793
01:03:01,043 --> 01:03:03,034
and his wife, one by one.

794
01:03:05,148 --> 01:03:07,582
He paid.

795
01:03:09,085 --> 01:03:13,078
American way is to...
What? Call the police, yes?

796
01:03:15,458 --> 01:03:17,756
But remember, I'm illegal.

797
01:03:19,128 --> 01:03:21,119
I have to do other way.

798
01:03:21,197 --> 01:03:24,758
Look, look, look.
I... I was schoolteacher, okay?

799
01:03:24,834 --> 01:03:26,893
The... The Russians invaded again.

800
01:03:26,969 --> 01:03:29,870
I had to spend five years
in refugee camp in Ingushetia.

801
01:03:29,939 --> 01:03:33,375
They want get rid of us,
Russians kill us if we go back.

802
01:03:33,442 --> 01:03:37,105
<i>[Adam]
Ah.! Aha.!
[ Clapping]</i>

803
01:03:37,180 --> 01:03:40,274
America... that is it.
That is all I dreamed of.

804
01:03:40,349 --> 01:03:43,216
To have my family
here with me together again.

805
01:03:43,286 --> 01:03:47,279
<i>That is what I working for.
That is what I paid you for.
Here.</i>

806
01:03:47,356 --> 01:03:50,348
Contact these people.
Maybe they can tell you something.

807
01:03:51,360 --> 01:03:55,490
Here. Take it.
I'm just the guy who puts people
in touch with other people.

808
01:03:55,565 --> 01:03:57,624
Take an advance, okay?

809
01:03:57,700 --> 01:04:00,567
Keep the cab for a couple of days.
I don't care.

810
01:04:01,737 --> 01:04:04,137
Just leave me alone.

811
01:04:07,476 --> 01:04:09,410
<i>[Whistle Blows]</i>

812
01:04:11,981 --> 01:04:13,972
<i>[ Chattering]</i>

813
01:04:18,054 --> 01:04:20,420
<i>[Gholab Speaking Foreign Language]</i>

814
01:04:23,092 --> 01:04:26,152
He says he brought down
a Russian helicopter
with one of these.

815
01:04:26,229 --> 01:04:28,197
<i>Yes.! Fall down.!
Fall down.!
My ass, he did.</i>

816
01:04:28,264 --> 01:04:31,756
You ask him, uh,
if he's got any, uh, mines.
Claymore mines.

817
01:04:31,834 --> 01:04:34,928
Uh, claymore.
Claymore. Mines.
Mines.

818
01:04:35,004 --> 01:04:37,165
Yes. Yes. Come, come, brother.

819
01:04:38,241 --> 01:04:41,176
Mines.

820
01:04:41,244 --> 01:04:43,235
Switch. Yes.

821
01:04:43,312 --> 01:04:45,371
And a remote.

822
01:04:45,448 --> 01:04:48,713
- For what do we need claymore?
- You just never know.

823
01:04:48,784 --> 01:04:51,252
[Foreign Language]

824
01:04:52,788 --> 01:04:54,722
Tap. Keeyo!

825
01:04:57,193 --> 01:04:58,626
Done!

826
01:05:04,333 --> 01:05:06,460
Adam.

827
01:05:06,535 --> 01:05:08,730
Uh, I come with you.

828
01:05:08,804 --> 01:05:11,602
Let me do this... alone.
No, she is my sister.

829
01:05:11,674 --> 01:05:15,041
I will come back.
I tell you what happened.
No, Adam. It's not just that.

830
01:05:15,111 --> 01:05:17,671
I have to see it.
I have to see where.

831
01:05:18,781 --> 01:05:21,147
Under... Understand me.

832
01:05:21,217 --> 01:05:24,311
There has to be some way
to say good-bye.

833
01:05:26,656 --> 01:05:28,624
Maybe they're not dead.

834
01:05:28,691 --> 01:05:30,784
How do we know?

835
01:05:30,860 --> 01:05:33,658
Huh? There is still a chance. No?

836
01:05:33,729 --> 01:05:35,822
Maybe not everybody died.

837
01:05:37,199 --> 01:05:39,667
You stay here and wait for me.

838
01:05:47,343 --> 01:05:51,245
<i>Listen, if it were up to me,
I'd give you a couple days to grieve.</i>

839
01:05:51,314 --> 01:05:53,248
But you're just
the middleman, right?

840
01:05:54,250 --> 01:05:58,653
Your company has a regular,
legitimate trade with China, Taiwan,

841
01:05:58,721 --> 01:06:00,655
Indonesia and the Philippines.

842
01:06:00,723 --> 01:06:03,692
Now, from time to time,
your father would give us
a container number,

843
01:06:03,759 --> 01:06:05,852
what port it's coming from,
name of the ship.

844
01:06:05,928 --> 01:06:07,862
I mean, take a look.

845
01:06:07,930 --> 01:06:10,694
<i>Two, three million of these
come through here every year.</i>

846
01:06:10,766 --> 01:06:13,394
Now what's the odds against
any one of them being searched?

847
01:06:13,469 --> 01:06:16,802
Whatever they are,
I don't have the option
of closing down the company.

848
01:06:16,872 --> 01:06:21,138
Is that what you're telling me?
We'd like to keep the relationship
going with you. Yes.

849
01:06:21,210 --> 01:06:23,144
Relationship?

850
01:06:23,212 --> 01:06:26,477
First you stick me up
for a quarter mil.
Then you burn my car.

851
01:06:26,549 --> 01:06:32,112
Now you won't even let me
bury my dad without trying to
nail my ass to something else?

852
01:06:32,188 --> 01:06:34,554
<i>You need to work on
your relationships, pal.</i>

853
01:06:34,623 --> 01:06:37,319
And you need to remember
that this is the real world,

854
01:06:37,393 --> 01:06:41,159
and in the real world
you're just a loser who can't pay
the bills now that daddy's gone.

855
01:06:41,230 --> 01:06:43,630
You do as you're told.

856
01:06:43,699 --> 01:06:47,157
And one funeral in the family
is enough, isn't it?

857
01:06:49,538 --> 01:06:51,938
We have a container
coming in today.

858
01:06:52,008 --> 01:06:55,739
We need somewhere to unload it...
somewhere quiet,
used to handling overseas freight,

859
01:06:55,811 --> 01:06:57,745
near the freeway.

860
01:06:57,813 --> 01:07:01,749
You tell security
you're expecting a delivery,
make sure nobody's workin' late.

861
01:07:01,817 --> 01:07:05,253
- That's all you have to do.
- And maybe go to prison for 10 years.

862
01:07:22,505 --> 01:07:24,666
<i>[Man]
There's a guy coming up to see you.</i>

863
01:07:24,740 --> 01:07:27,504
Uh, uh, Adam.
I don't know his last name.

864
01:07:27,576 --> 01:07:29,840
Uh, Chechen.

865
01:07:29,912 --> 01:07:32,176
<i>Let me put it this way.</i>

866
01:07:32,248 --> 01:07:37,049
<i>I don't need him coming back here
asking, uh, too many questions
anytime soon, okay?</i>

867
01:07:44,527 --> 01:07:47,519
<i>[Ship Horn Blows]
[Seagull Squawking]</i>

868
01:07:51,634 --> 01:07:55,070
<i>Do you know
the name of the boat?
He said, ''Star Pacific. ''</i>

869
01:08:00,376 --> 01:08:01,968
There.

870
01:08:02,044 --> 01:08:04,308
<i>[Men Chattering]</i>

871
01:08:13,355 --> 01:08:16,415
Why don't you wait here?
Uh, let me speak to them.

872
01:08:16,492 --> 01:08:18,483
<i>No. I'm going too.</i>

873
01:08:20,496 --> 01:08:25,160
<i>No, we don't want to cause anybody trouble.
We don't want blame anyone.</i>

874
01:08:25,234 --> 01:08:27,225
This is my sister-in-law.

875
01:08:27,303 --> 01:08:29,771
She... She lost her sister.

876
01:08:29,839 --> 01:08:31,830
I lose my... my wife, my daughter.

877
01:08:31,907 --> 01:08:33,875
Little... Little girl.

878
01:08:33,943 --> 01:08:38,346
Yeah, well, we're just the guys
that meet the ships, you know?

879
01:08:38,414 --> 01:08:41,850
We never know
what's coming in half the time.
We get the phone call, we go out.

880
01:08:43,819 --> 01:08:45,684
<i>Some nights it's packages.</i>

881
01:08:49,425 --> 01:08:51,552
<i>- Other nights it's illegals.
- [Adam]
People.</i>

882
01:08:51,627 --> 01:08:53,595
<i>- Huh?
- Let's go.</i>

883
01:08:53,662 --> 01:08:56,460
<i>People. It is people.
Human beings.</i>

884
01:08:56,532 --> 01:08:59,968
- Yeah. All right.
People. Whatever.
- My wife and daughter is...

885
01:09:00,035 --> 01:09:02,367
<i>[Wayne]
Take 'em someplace quiet.</i>

886
01:09:03,606 --> 01:09:05,938
<i>There's transport waitin'for 'em.</i>

887
01:09:06,008 --> 01:09:08,772
<i>After that, it's none of our business.</i>

888
01:09:23,792 --> 01:09:26,192
How can ship go down
just like that?

889
01:09:26,262 --> 01:09:29,561
<i>That's a dangerous piece
of water out there, boy.
It can take a ship any size.</i>

890
01:09:29,632 --> 01:09:32,226
- With no warning? Nothing?
- Sorry to hear about your family.

891
01:09:32,301 --> 01:09:35,566
<i>It could have hit a reef, sprung a plate.
Anything could have happened.</i>

892
01:09:35,638 --> 01:09:39,665
Yeah, everybody did what they could.
Okay? You gotta believe that.
I mean, this is how we make a living.

893
01:09:39,742 --> 01:09:41,471
No.
You think we wanna
lose a ship that size?

894
01:09:41,544 --> 01:09:44,479
<i>- Come on.
- [Wayne]
That's our payday, buddy.</i>

895
01:09:44,547 --> 01:09:47,175
Adam, we go.
Adam, we go.

896
01:09:48,384 --> 01:09:50,443
Go. Go.

897
01:09:52,721 --> 01:09:56,418
Jesus.
What did I tell you, huh?

898
01:09:56,492 --> 01:09:59,256
<i>- [Wayne]
Shut up.!
- Come on, Adam.</i>

899
01:09:59,328 --> 01:10:01,922
We go to the morgue
to identify bodies.

